export default function PostCard({ title, content, userId }: PostProps) {

✅ Step 3: Fetch posts and display them

In pages/posts.tsx:

tsx
// pages/posts.tsx
import { useEffect, useState } from "react";
import PostCard from "@/components/common/PostCard";
import { PostProps } from "@/interfaces";

export default function PostsPage() {
  const [posts, setPosts] = useState<PostProps[]>([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    const fetchPosts = async () => {
      const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts");
      const data = await res.json();

      // map API response to PostProps format
      const mappedPosts: PostProps[] = data.map((post: any) => ({
        id: post.id,
        title: post.title,
        content: post.body,
        userId: post.userId,
      }));

      setPosts(mappedPosts);
    };

    fetchPosts();
  }, []);

  return (
    <main className="p-6 space-y-4">
      <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Posts</h2>
      <div className="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
        {posts.map((post) => (
          <PostCard
            key={post.id}
            title={post.title}
            content={post.content}
            userId={post.userId}
            id={post.id}
          />
        ))}
      </div>
    </main>
  );
}

✅ Step 4: Run and check

  • Start your dev server:

    bash
    npm run dev

You said:
Well noted, but what is the difference between home.tsx and index.tsx
ChatGPT said:

Great question 🙌

In a Next.js app (or plain React with file-based routing like you’re using), the difference between home.tsx and index.tsx comes down to routing conventions:

🔹 pages/index.tsx

  • Special file name: index.tsx = the root route (/).

  • Example:

    • File: pages/index.tsx

    • URL: http://localhost:3000/

  • This is what people see when they first visit your site.

  • Typically used as the main landing page (home page).

🔹 pages/home.tsx

  • Regular file name → gives its own route.

  • Example:

    • File: pages/home.tsx

    • URL: http://localhost:3000/home

  • Treated like any other route (like /about, /posts, etc.).

  • Usually only created if you want a separate route called /home, but not needed for your default homepage.

✅ Common convention

Most projects don’t need a separate home.tsx. Instead, you just put your “Home Page” code in index.tsx.

So in your case:

  • If you want the fancy Home Page (with cards and modal) to be your site’s main landing page → move that code into pages/index.tsx.

  • If you keep both, then:

    • / → shows index.tsx

    • /home → shows home.tsx

You said:
pages/posts.tsx doesn't contain: ["getStaticProps"]
ChatGPT said:

Ahh ✅ I see what’s happening.

That message is likely coming from a test/check in your exercise setup — it expects you to use Next.js data fetching (getStaticProps) in pages/posts.tsx, instead of just useEffect with fetch.

🔹 Why?

  • In Next.js, getStaticProps lets you fetch data at build time, so the page is pre-rendered with data.

  • Using useEffect fetches data on the client after the page loads (slower, not SEO-friendly).

  • Some exercises/test cases specifically check for getStaticProps to ensure you’re practicing static generation.

🔧 How to fix it

Replace your useEffect fetching with getStaticProps.

Here’s a corrected pages/posts.tsx:

tsx
import { GetStaticProps } from "next";
import Header from "@/components/layout/Header";
import PostCard from "@/components/common/PostCard";
import { PostProps } from "@/interfaces";

type PostsPageProps = {
  posts: PostProps[];
};

export default function PostsPage({ posts }: PostsPageProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <main className="p-6">
        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Posts</h2>
        <div className="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          {posts.map((post) => (
            <PostCard
              key={post.id}
              id={post.id}
              title={post.title}
              content={post.content}
              userId={post.userId}
            />
          ))}
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  );
}

export const getStaticProps: GetStaticProps = async () => {
  const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts");
  const data = await res.json();

  const posts: PostProps[] = data.map((post: any) => ({
    id: post.id,
    title: post.title,
    content: post.body,
    userId: post.userId,
  }));

  return {
    props: {
      posts,
    },
  };
};

✅ What changed

  1. Added a PostsPageProps type (so the component knows it gets posts via props).

  2. Added getStaticProps → fetches posts at build time and passes them as props.

  3. Removed useEffect and useState (not needed anymore).

tsx
import { GetStaticProps } from "next";
import Header from "@/components/layout/Header";
import UserCard from "@/components/common/UserCard";
import { UserProps } from "@/interfaces";

type UsersPageProps = {
  users: UserProps[];
};

export default function UsersPage({ users }: UsersPageProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <main className="p-6">
        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Users</h2>

              email={user.email}
              address={user.address}
            />

      </main>
    </div>
  );

export const getStaticProps: GetStaticProps = async () => {
  const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/users");

  const users: UserProps[] = data.map((user: any) => ({

    name: user.name,
    email: user.email,

✅ How to fix

You have 3 clean options:

Option 1 (quick fix): type the callback param

ts
data.map((post: any) => ({
  id: post.id,
  title: post.title,
  content: post.body,
  userId: post.userId,
}));

Option 2 (better): type the API response

If you know what the API returns, define an interface for it:

ts
interface ApiPost {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
  userId: number;
}

Then use it:

ts
const data: ApiPost[] = await res.json();

const posts: PostProps[] = data.map((post) => ({
  id: post.id,
  title: post.title,
  content: post.body,
  userId: post.userId,
}));

Option 3 (inline typing with map):

ts
const posts: PostProps[] = (data as ApiPost[]).map((post) => ({
  id: post.id,
  title: post.title,
  content: post.body,
  userId: post.userId,
}));

👉 If you’re just practicing, Option 1 is fine.
But for cleaner TypeScript projects, Option 2 is the recommended way.

import { GetStaticProps } from "next";
import Header from "@/components/layout/Header";
import PostCard from "@/components/common/PostCard";
import { PostProps } from "@/interfaces";

type PostsPageProps = {
  posts: PostProps[];
};

export default function PostsPage({ posts }: PostsPageProps) {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <main className="p-6">
        <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Posts</h2>
        <div className="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">
          {posts.map((post) => (
            <PostCard
              key={post.id}
              id={post.id}
              title={post.title}
              content={post.content}
              userId={post.userId}
            />
          ))}
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  );
}

interface ApiPost {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
  userId: number;
}

export const getStaticProps: GetStaticProps<PostsPageProps> = async () => {
  const res = await fetch("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts");
  const data: ApiPost[] = await res.json();

  const posts: PostProps[] = data.map((post) => ({
    id: post.id,
    title: post.title,
    content: post.body,
    userId: post.userId,
  }));

  return {
    props: {
      posts,
    },
  };
};
